Data Analysis

Research Question 1

Question a).What is the correlation between sentiment polarity and sentiment subjectivity of app reviews?

#Calculate the average sentiment polarity and sentiment subjectivity for each app in the googleplayreview dataset
googleplayreviews <-
  googleplayreview %>%
  filter(Sentiment != "nan") %>%
  group_by(App) %>%
  summarise(total=n(),
            avgPolarity= mean(Sentiment_Polarity),
            avgSubjectivity = mean(Sentiment_Subjectivity)) 
#plot the relationship between sentiment polarity and sentiment subjectivity
regressionplot <-
  googleplayreviews%>%
  ggplot(aes(y = avgPolarity, x = avgSubjectivity))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se = FALSE)
print(regressionplot + ggtitle("Correlation between Sentiment Polarity and Sentiment Subjectivty of App reviews "))


Answer: From the plot, there is a strong, positive and linear relationship between Sentiment Polarity and Sentiment Subjectivty.

Question b).What app has both high values of sentiment polarity and subjectivity, which are greater than 0.7?

#get the top 20 apps which has high sentiment Polarity 
a <-
  googleplayreviews %>%
  arrange(desc(avgPolarity)) %>%
  head(20)
#Draw the scatter plot to see the app whose sentiment sujectivity and polarity are both greater than 0,.7
a %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=avgPolarity, y=avgSubjectivity)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=App))


Answer: Daily Workouts - Exercise Fitness Routine Trainer and Google Slides have both high values of sentiment polarity and subjectivity which are greater than 0.7.

Research Question 2

Question: What’s the relationship between Rating, sentiment Subjectivity, sentiment Polarity?

#Join two dataset by "App"
TopRating <-
  googleplaystore %>%
  inner_join(googleplayreviews) %>% 
  select( App = App, Rating, avgPolarity,avgSubjectivity,Category ) %>%
  group_by(App,avgPolarity,Rating,avgSubjectivity,Category) %>%
  summarise(total=n(),
            avgRating= mean(Rating))
Joining, by = "App"
Column `App` joining factors with different levels, coercing to character vector
TopRating
d<-
  TopRating %>%
  select(Rating,avgSubjectivity,avgPolarity)%>%
  na.omit()
Adding missing grouping variables: `App`
#model the sentiment subjectvity and sentiment polarity as the factors for Rating
mod1<- party::ctree(
    Rating ~ avgSubjectivity+avgPolarity,
    data=d)
plot(mod1,type="simple")

Answer: From the decision tree plot, we can see that sentiment Subjectivity and sentiment Polarity influence on the value of Rating.

Research Question 3

Question: What apps contained in the googleplaystore_user_reviews dataset have high average rating which is greater than 4.6? Find the pattern of high rating apps.

# unique App in googleplaystore dataset
googleplaystore %>%
  summarise(n_distinct(App))
# unique App in googlestore_user_reviews dataset after NA value deleted 
googleplayreviews %>%
  summarise(n_distinct(App))
#Join the tables of googleplaystore and googleplayreviews. Get the app whose average rating is not less than 4.8
TopRating2 <-
  TopRating %>%
  filter(avgRating >= 4.7)
TopRating2
#Inspect the average sentiment polartiy of high rating app 
TopRating2 %>%
  group_by(avgRating,avgPolarity) %>% 
  summarise(count =n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=avgRating,y=avgPolarity, group=avgRating))+
  geom_boxplot()

TopRating2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=avgRating,y=avgPolarity,color = Category))+
  geom_point()


Answer: The TopRating table includes 64 Apps have greater than 4.6 average rating.From boxplot, we can see apps who have 4.8 average rating have highest variability of sentiment polarity since the range of middle boxplot is largest one.From the scatterplot, we can see the high rating apps mostly fall into 4.7 rating.

Research Question 4

How many apps are there which have common use words you’re interested in? Examine them visually to find new app common name to add to the pattern, e.g. Free.

#get the unique app names in googleplaystore dataset
Distinctapp <-
  googleplaystore %>%
  group_by(App)%>%
  summarise(total=n())
Distinctapp
#App names which have below expression I want to extratct
pattern <- "(Art|Health|Google|Police|English|Beauty|Chat|Photo|Scan|Music|Free|Book|Mobile|Call|Learn|Home)"
#Set of matches extracted
AppNames <-
  Distinctapp %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern, App)) %>%
  tidyr::extract(App, into = "name", regex = pattern)
#frequency table
AppNameFrequency <-
  AppNames %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  summarise(count =n()) %>%
  mutate(name = reorder(name,desc(count))) %>%
  arrange(desc(count))
AppNameFrequency
#bar chart of frequency
AppNameFrequency %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= name,y=count)) +
  geom_bar(stat='identity',width=0.5) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1 ))


ANswer: From the histogram of 16 patterns I identify, the App names including “Free” are the most .
